segments.text: For four years, I worked with Ms. Walton, and she's one of the sweetest women I've seen in my life.
And when I graduated, she gave me $25, which was a lot of money.
Describe, in personality, describe the Waltons, both.
Well, as I said, Ms. Walton was just like a mother.
we always have something on that table.
And that's where I learned that a president's wife has something more to worry about than what's on that flower table, what she has on the table.
So that we made, I observed what she did as a president's wife and how she entertained and she'd tell me what she did.
That was four years of good training with her.
I learned a lot about what a present wife is expected to do other than being his wife.
And I remember one night we bought flowers.
I think we bought a dozen Picardy glass.
It's that peach colored glass.
And I guess somebody, must have been Eleanor Roosevelt or somebody came, somebody big.
I know in that big living room with the whole house that burned was the most beautiful maroon carpet I thought I'd ever seen in my life.
And I had thought I'd never seen that much of it before.
And there was a beautiful crystal chandelier that hung over the stairway.
And in one of the remodeling things, that thing just disappeared.
I don't know where it went.
Somebody said, well, it was put up in the attic, but it never was found.
And it wasn't there when the house burned.
They know that.
Let me see what else.
Describe Mr. Walton in personality.
Well, he, as I remember him very much, he was bright bald and gray and a big round face.
I didn't see him very often, except every now and then Ms. Walton went in passing and we'd see.
But he knew that I was taking care of what she needed, and that's all he wanted to know, too.
That's the way it goes, you know.
But I learned right there.
how you take care of a president's wife.
And I was, you know, in Oklahoma, I was with Dr. Cross, Ms. Cross.
He was present 25 years.
And I took care, I knew right away that Ms. Cross, she was a great PR person much later than, I mean, the Waltons, you see.
And that's when the president's wife
was more active in a lot of things.
And she could think of things that would make him look good.
For instance, one Christmas, we had a student who grew a bunch of poinsettias.
And she herself delivered those poinsettias to old retired faculty people for Christmas.
And those people never forgot that.
And she told me a long time before she retired, before I got here, she says, we'll miss the flowers.
or anything we'll miss.
And I learned again, I learned again that from Ms. Walton.
It was Ms. Walton that taught me what to do and why.
And that was real good training.
And every time I went back to the campus, I went to see Ms. Walton and visited with her, and she'd ask me what I was doing and what I was doing.
I would do the things she taught me to do.
She loved that so much, which was right.
It was true.
She did a good job of it.
And I'd go back to see her every time and visit with her and talk to her about how I appreciated all she'd done for me.
And when she died, I was the only non-family member that was a pallbearer, which I cherish very much.
All together, Mr. Walton was so busy, and he just, I didn't see much of him.
Of course, you don't see much of a president, get it, back in those days.
There was not that much emphasis on academics for a president as there was later.
Where was the president's office in those years?
Let's see.
When did we get?
Was it down in that what is now the Jack Williams building?
Yes, it was.
They had a big room with a fireplace in it.
I remember that, oh yeah, that's where I first met, who was the last secretary down there, so long.
I'll never forget her.
Anyway, it was at that, also, you remember the beautiful stairway at Travertine Marble?
It was so soft, people cut it with their fingernails.
It ruined it.
Let's see, when you were a student, the YMCA was a center of activity.
Everything.
That's where Yale practiced.
They had Yale practice in front of that until I'll be in my senior year.
And that got so big, they transferred it over to Henderson Hall, where the chimney sweeps came from.
And it got so big that we couldn't handle it there anymore.
I do remember.
Do you remember Guyon Hall?
Sure.
Well, you know, there were two trees in that bed in front of Guyon Hall, Cedar Elms.
And so they moved them, and we put one just to the, as you face the YMCA, we put one just to the right of the Y, Cedar Elm.
It was still there the last time I knew.
And then
When they got ready to tear down Guyon, I begged them to.
There's this beautiful columns, fluted-iron columns, and the tablature above said, Ignorance is the curse of God, knowledge of the wind will fly to the world, it will fly to heaven by Shakespeare.
I begged them to say that the tablature or one of the columns or something as a memorial.
And I was told that they didn't have enough money for that kind of food, so they took it down and threw it away.
Every bit of it.
What did you students do at the Y?
Well, first of all, that was the Cases Confectionery.
That's the only place you could get a drink on that whole area of town.
And Cases Confectionery was good.
You'd get sandwiches and things there, if you had any money.
There was one telephone there, and you could use it just so long that you had to get off.
And if you didn't get off, somebody got you off.
And that was in the, just off the lobby of it.
Why?
And of course, there was no newspapers there and everything like that.
And you could come, you could get over there and escape the sophomores sometimes.
Were there some pool tables?
Yes, and I'm trying to think where the, well, the pool table was in the basement.
There at one time was a small pool down there, but I believe they'd covered it over and made a pool all out of it.
Yeah, I'm sure, I think that's the time that they had done away with the pool.
The pool was so small that you couldn't get in or out of it hardly.
Did you know Mr. Cashin?
Oh, yes.
Describe him, please.
I think the brother had a set over the land with any more glasses.
And I knew this Red Cajun, yeah.
He had two little boys.
Yeah, two little boys.
Yes, I knew Mr. Cajun.
And he had a good program going there for the time.
Those two little boys, did you see much of them on the campus, Red and Jim?
I knew Red Cash because he played football.
I couldn't remember the little boy's name if I had to.
You said Jim, yeah.
Jim played one year, then went away to the war, and then came back right after the war and played for Coach Norton.
He's retired back there now.
Oh, good.
Let's see, were there religious activities at the Y?
Yes.
That's where Mr. Hensel's funeral was held, in the Y.
When was that?
You know, I can't tell you.
I wrote all that up in a single... Was it after you were away?
Oh, yeah, I was in Oklahoma.
I got back for the funeral, and I remember I never will forget because all of a sudden the lens fell out of my right side and I had glasses, and I didn't have any glasses.
Then we went over to Ms. Henson's for a meal, but...
I forgot who the pallbearers were.
I know I was not.
Because they were not sure I'd get there in time.
But that's all right.
I kept up with Miss Ansel after that.
Every time I'd go, I'd go see her regularly.
And I'd take her something.
And when she died, Bill said that you have been nicer to my mother than anybody else has.
Of course, I was loyal to Ms. Jensel, and every now and then, Buddy Benz would give me an orchid or two, and I'd give them to her before we got the Benz school up there.
See, that was another thing we did.
Buddy Benz had the Benz School of Design and had written three books on it.
He probably knew all that.
Anyway, if you happen to see Jim Johnson, he's got it.
He's done a fantastic job with that school of bed, school of design.
And it was set up in a real will.
He had that set up by a lawyer in the will.
This I probably shouldn't tell you, but right after Ben's death, Mr. Dean Kunkel called us down and said, I want you to make an endowed
scholarship, I mean endowed, professorship, and I'm going to use the rest of the money for biochemistry research.
And I said, no, Dean, I'm sorry, but you can't have any of that money.
And he said, why not?
I said, because it's set up in the will, tied up, has to be spent.
And if you violate the will, we won't get any of it.
I said, even he knew.
Buddy knew certain things like that disappeared around there.
And I said, he had a large fan that fixed it tight where nobody could touch it except for that one purpose.
And that's the way it's been.
Thank goodness, because it has become now the school of floral design.
In fact, see, Buddy and his two sisters made that an endowed chair.
And that's when he wanted to make an endowed chair.
professorship and not a chair.
And I said, you can't do it.
And he thought, gee, you know, nobody had ever told the dean he couldn't.
But I knew I had to, so I did.
What kind of activities went on at Guyon Hall?
What did a student go to see at Guyon Hall?
We had assemblies there, is all I can tell you.
And it was on a flat floor.
You couldn't see anything.
Oh, every activity of any size was in there.
They had the assembly hall, too, which was, what did we do in the assembly hall?
Assembly hall was where they had picture shows, yeah.
How often did you go to the movie?
I never did go.
I didn't have any money.
What did you spend any money on?
What did you spend for fun?
But it didn't induce me, really.
We were going to school and borrowed money, so I didn't spend a lot for anything.
I'm trying to think.
That's been so far back.
I guess I got to go to a picture show now and then at the assembly hall.
That was an interesting old wooden structure.
They had all the class meetings there and class elections and those things.
Now, it was west of Sabisa.
Let me think.
It was... Toward the railroad from Sabisa?
Well, it was toward Guyon Hall.
Oh.
Okay.
Over about where the chapel is now.
Yeah, it was.
The chapel backed up to it at one time, I believe.
Here in the right... That may be where it was.
the chapel may take its site.
Because it wasn't Lowell Hall next to it.
It was next to Lowell Hall.
I remember there was a very narrow walk between Lowell Hall and the assembly hall.
Who were some famous people that came to the campus while you were a student?
Describe that, please.
Well, we had a
We had everybody lined completely around Kyle Field.
And he rode by in the car of the limousine with the Secret Service man with him.
And then they had lunch on the farm or something.
Then we had a parade, a review fire on Drillfield.
But that's the biggest man I guess we had come.
And then I think Elder came later.
When he came, were you aware of his physical disabilities?
Oh, yeah.
We saw him in Africa with us during the war.
Oh, I know you did during the war.
But someone told me that when he came to visit A&M that time, there were no photographers allowed to take a picture of his... Well, I know he had his wheelchair.
Yeah, I guess it was a wheelchair.
Come to think of it, I don't know.
They didn't take any pictures.
Anyway...
All right, Mrs. Roosevelt came.
Do you remember any other famous celebrities?
I don't remember.
Entertainers?
Big bands?
Well, we had the big bands.
We had Glenn Gray.
We had Duke Ellington.
Those I remember.
And...
This is a big band era.
They had those down for the military balls and for the junior, senior prom.
We had the big name bands.
Did you go to those dances?
I worked a deal.
The social secretary, they wanted some plants around the bandstand.
And they had to get permission from Mr. Hensel each time they had one.
So I made a deal that if they gave me a package of dances, I'd get the permits every week.
So I'd see Mr. Hensel the whole time, and I'd get the thing filled out for him.
And so they gave me a package.
I got to give all the dances free.
How did Aggies behave at those dances?
What were they like?
Very well behaved.
Very well behaved.
There might have been one or two out of line, but they didn't stay out of line.
Aggies, this was them.
But when we had the infantry ball,
For instance, you were supposed to dance with everybody from your company that day at one time.
So they got in a rush.
And you were sometimes just a continual tag.
But you didn't have to do it.
I don't believe I saw very much misbehavior anywhere unless it was after the dance was over and those things.
And I didn't see that.
We moved out of the dormitories.
And girls would move in there for one dance, or whatever happened to be the occasion.
See, in the infantry ball, they moved out to Hart Hall, and the girls stayed in Hart Hall.
And I was lucky.
One of my professors and his wife had a freedom of their own.
So you tried to get a place for them to stay.
But if you could, you'd put it in a dormitory.
The big dances and everything, young ladies came down on the train or on the buses?
Well, sometimes they came on buses from the CIA, Texas State College for Women.
Sometimes they'd come on the train.
There wasn't much motor transportation then.
We had cars.
We didn't have too many cars.
I remember my senior year, we had one car that old boy borrowed, brought home, brought down for home, and somebody wrecked it.
Bill Turner.
Now, did you ever have any special dates during that era?
Did you and Freda know each other then?
Oh, we grew up together in the same town.
Okay.
We knew all the in-laws and out-laws on both sides.
Did you bring her down for some of those dances?
She came down for them, but I guess we came on the train.
All the way from Franklin to College Station on the train?
No, she was in Baylor, in Waco.
Oh, wow.
And, you know, I don't remember how we got there.
I don't know.
We didn't have a car or anything.
They didn't have a car.
But anyway, we got there.
And we had good dances there.
Friedrich remembers a lot about the dances too.
All right.
The religious activities around the campus, did you and your buddies go to church ever?
Yeah, we had a church.
We had a church, a Baptist church at the North Gate.
And we'd go up there.
I used to know the preacher's name.
I've forgotten it now.
But we went to church regularly.
As regularly as you can, I guess.
Was there a religious emphasis week then?
No.
That wasn't?
I can't tell you.
I don't remember.
What about athletics?
Describe a Saturday home football day.
What did that day include?
When did it begin?
It began at Reveille.
I went to bed at Taps.
But I remember...
We had not beaten TCU in 10 years, and we beat them in 37, I think it was.
And somebody made a grave on the end of the, you know where the bugle stand used to be?
Bell and Jimmy, all right.
Somebody made a grave there and put it through the boom.
It says, here lies a TCU jinx.
Dead no longer stinks.
And later in Oklahoma, I had a flower shop.
And we meet somebody, Texas, I guess.
And I put a little grave in the window.
A little boy came in and offered me $100.
I said, you can have it.
But
I remember that Homer Arden, that week, had a big stand built.
And he'd say, hit him again.
He kept laying flat on his back.
And that was Sammy Ball.
And they'd have him laying flat on his back all afternoon.
And they beat TCU for the first time in 10 years.
All right.
Now, those football days, you'd get up early in the morning.
And what'd you all do on the Saturday morning of a home game other than go to class?
Well, we had Saturday classes in between.
I guess we got out of Franklin to Haskell.
I don't remember what we did.
Was there a pass-by in those days?
Did you march in for review at the game?
No.
No.
No, the core was a later thing.
But I remember that.
All right, and you stood at the game with your date.
You stood at the game with your date.
And we were never allowed to sit down any time.
And if you won the game, whose job was it to go get the yell leaders?
That came later, too.
Oh, really?
Oh, so.
Well, we didn't have a fish pond until the class of 38.
Now, let me think.
I guess they went after them, but I don't know who went after them or what they did with them.
You see, the class of 38 gave that fountain, and it's been repaired and worked over so many times.
And I know when we had our one reunion, I asked them if they would repair it and have it running for that occasion.
They said, yeah, we've already spent so much money on that thing that we don't want to spend any more.
Who suggested that the class of 38 give the fish pond?
Do you know?
I don't know who suggested it.
I guess John Bone.
And John Bowman was like his president, I'm sure.
I know he did, because he told me one time he had a whole series of letters from Mr. Enzo back and forth between the two.
And I said, well, if you give me those letters, I'd like to have them and put them in the archive.
But he never got around to give them to me.
So anyway, I know that John was in on it, of course, as president.
And there was someone else that keeps reminding us that everybody, somebody owed so much money on that pond, yeah.
And I forgot who it was.
It was somebody from West Texas, from Midland.
I can't prove his name out right now.
After a home victory, where did Aggies go to celebrate on Saturday night?
What's that bridge down that road?
Uncle Ed's?
Uncle Ed's.
Oh, you can find him there all the time.
And how was that name?
Was it H-Y-R-D?
Maybe Hard Liquor.
Well, I know it was Hard Liquor, but was it a Czech name?
Yeah.
Because I've tried to find out H-Y-R-D-L-Y-C-K-A or whatever it was.
I don't think you're close on that one.
Okay.
I don't know.
That should be somewhere.
It should be in this row somewhere.
Because everybody went there.
Describe the place.
How big was it?
I didn't go.
Oh, you didn't go?
I didn't drink beer.
I didn't go.
Let's see.
Basketball.
Describe DeWare Fieldhouse and what it was like to go to a game there.
It was worse than the Holler House on the Browns I ever thought about, Mick.
It was so small.
And they only had seats on each side.
It wasn't an oval.
And very few people got to go because there just wasn't enough room.
Describe the Aggie student body.
What was a typical Aggie student in those days?
Where were Aggies from?
What were their attitudes?
Were they city boys or country boys?
I guess they were more from the city than they were from the country, I'd say.
Maybe 60-40, maybe.
They all came to A&M because of the leadership.
built in, everybody came in because they wanted to.
And they weren't pushed there at all.
And some went because people in their hometown had gone there and different reasons like that.
The current word is diversity.
How diverse was the student body then?
Not very diverse.
Do you remember some Catholic boys?
Jewish?
Let me think of it.
I know we had both of them.
I had friends with both of them.
but I can't remember the names right now.
Let's see.
I can't remember who they were.
Were there some Hispanic?
Very few, very few.
Were there some that were rich?
Well, I don't know whether they were or not.
I worked all the time, so I didn't know.
I do know that some of the boys on the corps staff didn't worry about money.
They seemed to be all right.
And I guess some of them had enough money they didn't have to worry about anything.
But I never was familiar.
I had one friend that was a freshman with me, and his stepdaddy was a banker, and he sent him out with a checkbook.
And you know, that's when one semester flunked everything there was.
And he went to Baylor and did the same thing.
So he and his brother ended up in the Air Corps.
They both came out of the war all right, but they didn't go back to school.
You spent more money in one year than I spent the whole time, four or five years.
Do you have any idea what a year cost at A&M in those days?
I can tell you.
My class president who just died at our last reunion told us that he spent
Total or total?
First year.
And he ended up as a banker.
The big student organizations then, the core was the ultimate.
What other organizations were there with high prestige?
Well, we had the Ross Volunteers.
I got a bid at Ross Vaughan, too, and I didn't have a hundred dollars to buy a uniform with.
And I understand there were a couple or three secret fraternities on campus, but I don't know what they were.
It was rumored.
Do you know what their names were?
I think True Texans was one.
That's the one I can recall.
All right, now I've heard of another one called the Stickers.
Never heard of that one.

uh... what was their purpose do you have any idea what was there reason for being like fraternity two or three people have offered this the gas that their primary reason was to try to get their members as core commanders uh... that to get their group in the key positions working on monday i i wouldn't want anything
I worked an awful lot.
Other than that, I was in class or at work nine hours a day.
And that don't leave you a lot of time.
I didn't get around a lot and make a lot of friends.
My very best friend was killed at the beginning of our senior year in an airplane crash.
David Murphy from Ohio.
They were...
chasing that Bloomingdale Railroad train.
Uh-oh.
And hit something down, there went two of them.
Other organizations, how prestigious was the Aggie band then?
Oh, it's always been one of the best things there.
It's always been the hardest thing to get in, too.
You had to be a good musician, always.
It's gotten so big now that they have our specialties, all of them.
What about Yale leaders?
Was that important?
Oh, yes.
I remember they had the Yale leader elections every year.
And I remember, I'm trying to think of his name now.
But they had the Yale leader election every year.
We had Yale practice in front of Hawaii.
for a long time, then it went over to Henderson Hall.
Didn't last long before Henderson Hall, though.
That was popular because of so much mud, it rained.
But, uh... And, uh, was, uh...
I'm trying to think of somebody's name.
You remember the basketball player named, uh...
They were four brothers.
Well, we'll get it later.
And was it important to be the senior class president?
Well, I guess it was.
Because you all didn't have a student body president then, I don't think.
Senior class president was Tom Murrow.
He died a couple weeks ago.
And he was also a freshman class president.
No, he was freshman class president.
and captain of the band.
And John Bone was senior class president.
And John Bone went to work for the IBM.
And he met a lady, a girl from Norman, Oklahoma, who I know real well.
I've kept up with her all the years.
And then about three years ago, they had a tree day in Oklahoma, and invited me to come up as a special guest for planting trees, because I had planted over two hundred trees on that campus.
And then I had also planted a hundred and eight million through garden clubs on the project one year.
The president, who was a former senator, Boren, asked me to come up there, and they had a big program about the trees.
In the middle 30s, the water table dropped to 108 feet, and all the big trees on campus died.
So we replaced them, and I had the chance to choose
a tree of choice to replace them with, which was a red oak.
And they're now beautiful, beautiful fall colors.
And last time I was on that campus, I got to see those things in color.
Now that causes me to ask you to describe the planting of all of those live oak trees on the A&M campus.
It's a good story.
a professor of botany wanted to put American, uh, palms.
And he and Mr. Hensel had a debate.
Mr. Hensel once said, we'd be glad if it was to be the tree.
But when I went there in 34, they said put palms all the way down Ross Avenue.
When I went there in 34, there was
four left with the palms.
And in the last junior year, those froze.
They had no more palms on campus.
That's why we have the live oaks, the stenciled children.
When did the live oaks, when were they first put out going east?
All right, that's a good question.
Very few people know that story.
It's the only time that I was ever aware that they had an appropriation of money to buy trees.
But they put out trees less than two inches in diameter.
They cost $1.75 a piece.
And they came from Griffin's Nursery in Beaumont.
And of course they've done very well.
But... Do you remember how many there were in the purchase?
No, I don't.
I do know that that's what they told us.
But now later, when I was first there,
we'd establish the perimeter trees.
And I bought those from a nursery in Kingsville, yeah, down in the valley.
We could take those trees, they were two-inch trees, row-run, set them down in a row, take them as they come, for $200 apiece.
So they increased the load.
But we did the perimeter of the campus then.
And we put them 80 feet apart so they could grow, make a statement, and put them 80 feet back from the curb so they wouldn't have to cut them down, ever.
Which was later proved, because later they widened in Texas.
And thank goodness we didn't lose the trees.
But we lost one big tree in that expansion.
It was on the golf course, hanging over the curb.
But nobody could see that tree anyway.
It was out in the street.
Did you, as a student, help set out those first live oaks?
No.
But that's the only time we ever had money.
We collected acres every year and planted them in the greenhouse.

put them in a four-inch pot until they got about a foot or two tall, then took them out on what is now Canyon Hill, way out there across Bethel, and grew them in a nursery, and then brought them back to the campus.
Now, I do know that when they had the big ice storm in 1936 or 1937, some of those trees were two inches in diameter by then.
Between the Ag Building and the library,
and they got isolated and snapped in two.
We hauled brush off that campus for weeks and a lot of the big limbs came down too because they were isolated and got overweight.
Blessed with the gift of hindsight, were we well advised to concentrate on live oaks or would have been better to have had a variety of trees?
Well, I think that a variety would have been better.
But I think that the live oaks established the pattern.
And I think that a tree, a prominent tree of live oaks was all right.
A few others mixed in at the time would have been all right, I think.
But hindsight, as you say, is better than foresight.
I've often wondered that oak that the students now call the Century Oak.
The photographs that I have seen of the original Old Main building cause me to think that tree is not quite as old as the students think it is.
I don't think so.
It's just called the Century Oak because it's the biggest oak we have and it's one you can climb in.
A very historical oak.
Now, you remember some
Senior class gathered acorns and planted them and sold seedlings from the century oak.
I don't remember what class it was, but they did that to raise money for their class gift.
Let's see.
Project houses.
Oh, yeah.
Please describe them and the students who lived over there.
All right.
a doctor's name.
Dan Russell.
Dan Russell got the idea that they could come down there and bring groceries and food and cows, milk cows.
And the first one was in Brown.
And it went over so good, the university built those 12 down there.
And they worked hard.
They came out all right.
Many of them, oh boy, got to go to school through the project houses.
And when I went back to A&M, Morris Bloodworth was a Project House boy.
And he was head of soil and crop sciences.
And they'd have a Project House reunion every year.
But that worked very well.
And Dr. Russell should have been given a lot more recognition for it, I think, than he got.
Were they built while you were a student?
Yes.
Some of them were already there?
The first one, some were in Bryan.
But they built those while I was there.
And I'm trying to think of a...
I'm not sure they were either.
There was another one out on the Horticulture Farm that they made a project house for people from over around Crockett
I don't really know now.
Let me see.
Now, I do know this.
After we made the test gardens at A&M, Dr. Russell would come over and walk through those.
He got more kick and benefit from a test garden than I believe anybody else.
He would come over and spend hours studying the flowers.
They were all set up and labeled, you know.
And he, I'd see him over there lots of times.
after he retired, walking through, spending time with him.
And that did me a lot of good to see him, enjoy him.
He seemed always to be deeply concerned about students.
Yes, he was very.
He was very concerned about students and their well-being and how they were getting along.
Let's see.
Your senior boots, do you remember when you bought them?
